Update the video generation pipeline so that all 3D mock up videos are produced in 1080p resolution or higher. Apply these rules across the entire app:

Add a fixed resolution configuration to the Veo video generation call.
Wherever the video generation request is built, set the resolution to a minimum of 1920x1080. If the model supports higher resolutions, request the highest available (for example 4K if supported).

In the code where the video generation call is made, add or update the configuration object to include:

config: {
  resolution: "1080p",
  // If supported, upgrade to:
  // resolution: "4k",
  // or:
  // width: 1920,
  // height: 1080
}


Ensure all modes (Strict, Flexible, Ecommerce, Luxury, Complex Material, and Default 4X Engine) inherit this resolution requirement. They should never fall back to sub-1080p output.

Add a video resolution verification step to the QA loop. After generation:

Detect the actual video resolution returned by the model.

If the resolution is lower than 1080p, automatically regenerate the video with the required resolution settings.

Display an error message if the model cannot produce 1080p or higher, and attempt regeneration up to three times before failing.

Apply this rule globally. Any feature, mode, or future workflow that generates a video must comply with the 1080p or higher requirement.

End of change request.

I will add detailed hover tooltips to the `ModeSelector` component. These tooltips will explain exactly what assets are generated in each mode (e.g., "2 Flat Lays, 2 Static 3D Mockups"), ensuring the user knows precisely what to expect before clicking.

